!important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a> and it doesn=E2=
=80=99t work seamlessly<em>:=C2=A0</em>Companies generally announce quarter=
ly earnings shortly after the quarter ends, but there=E2=80=99s some period=
 of time when the company=E2=80=99s executives pretty much know what the ea=
rnings release will say, but it hasn=E2=80=99t been published yet. Or compa=
nies will often negotiate mergers without first announcing =E2=80=9Chey we=
=E2=80=99re in=C2=A0merger talks,=E2=80=9D which is something that investor=
s would probably want to know. But for the most part investors expect that =
most material information about the company will be made public in a relati=
vely timely way.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are not allowed=
 to insider trade: If you are an executive of a company, and you know somet=
hing material that=C2=A0<em>hasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>been disclosed =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the company is negotiating a merger, it will announce bad earnings=
 next week, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you are not allowed to trade the stock=
.</li> </ol> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These two things are related. In=
vestors are entitled to expect that, when they buy or sell a company=E2=80=
=99s stock, they know more or less everything about the company. Cases wher=
e corporate insiders know important news that hasn=E2=80=99t been disclosed=
 are supposed to be relatively rare.<a href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a=
> But when they do have that sort of material nonpublic information, they c=
an=E2=80=99t trade, because public investors reasonably expect to be able t=
o trade on a level playing field.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What abo=
ut private companies=3F</p> <ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-=
left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The essenti=
al fact about private companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0the thing that makes them =
=E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that they don=E2=80=99t have pu=
blic-company disclosure requirements. There=E2=80=99s no law that they have=
 to publish quarterly financial statements; there=E2=80=99s not even a law =
that they have to send their shareholders annual financial statements.<a hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;"> <span>[3]</span> </a> The relationship between private compan=
ies and their shareholders is a private matter to be negotiated among thems=
elves, not, for the most part, a matter of securities regulation. In fact a=
 lot of big private companies do share a lot of business and financial info=
rmation with their shareholders, because the shareholders want that and the=
 companies work for the shareholders. But that=E2=80=99s not because the ru=
les require it; it=E2=80=99s because the shareholders do.</li> <li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Are you allowed to insider trade=3F</li> </ol> <p sty=
